    <title>Combined summary - Proposed BIP for OP_CAT</title>
    <updated>2023-10-30T14:46:13.017779+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2023-October/022101.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email discusses the implementation of OP_CAT and its potential use cases in Bitcoin. The sender suggests adding support for CSFS as well. There is a discussion about the effectiveness and necessity of a "just CAT" softfork, with the sender expressing confusion about its value without compelling examples. Support is expressed for OP_CAT, along with reasonable resource-consumption limiters. Another participant agrees that using OP_SUCCESS126 instead of OP_SUCCESS80 would be preferable. The performance impact of a loop and the refactoring of interpreter code are also mentioned. A suggestion is made to consider rolling sha2 opcodes in addition to OP_CAT, and the need for larger tapscripts is explained. The correct order of concatenation using OP_CAT and potential backward compatibility issues are discussed. Ethan Heilman raises concerns about the small limit of 520 bytes and suggests considering the total stack size as the real limit. He acknowledges the possibility of increasing this limit in future tapscript versions and thanks Rusty for clarifying details.</summary>
